3BAC4FFF-9FCA-4AB9-B20B-733512078E88.displayText: •    Be able to describe electrolysis as a process in which electrical energy, from a direct current supply, decomposes electrolytes.
3BAC4FFF-9FCA-4AB9-B20B-733512078E88.level3: •    Be able to describe electrolysis as a process in which electrical energy, from a direct current supply, decomposes electrolytes.

F3533B9C-2C8D-4F18-B1BF-3C0C66E10CD1.displayText: •    Know that electrolytes are ionic compounds in the molten state or dissolved in water.
F3533B9C-2C8D-4F18-B1BF-3C0C66E10CD1.level3: •    Know that electrolytes are ionic compounds in the molten state or dissolved in water.

E429FB02-478E-49AB-A2C4-6832300E7C44.displayText: •    Be able to explain the movement Of ions during electrolysis, in which positively charged cations migrate to the negatively charged cathode, and negatively charged anions migrate to the positively charged anode.
E429FB02-478E-49AB-A2C4-6832300E7C44.level3: •    Be able to explain the movement Of ions during electrolysis, in which positively charged cations migrate to the negatively charged cathode, and negatively charged anions migrate to the positively charged anode.

87135ACE-79AE-4F54-9F9F-7F5410FBFE87.displayText: Be able to explain oxidation and reduction in terms of loss or gain of electrons.
87135ACE-79AE-4F54-9F9F-7F5410FBFE87.level3: Be able to explain oxidation and reduction in terms of loss or gain of electrons.

292786BE-EF3B-4BBF-9471-1A94D1FFC70F.displayText: •    Know that reduction occurs at the cathode and that oxidation occurs at the anode.
292786BE-EF3B-4BBF-9471-1A94D1FFC70F.level3: •    Know that reduction occurs at the cathode and that oxidation occurs at the anode.

CBEE4B65-5C8E-4821-99F7-A70B791C8DC5.displayText: •    Be able to predict the products of electrolysis of binary, ionic compounds in the molten state. • Be able to explain the formation Of the products in the electrolysis of molten lead bromide using inert electrodes.
CBEE4B65-5C8E-4821-99F7-A70B791C8DC5.level3: •    Be able to predict the products of electrolysis of binary, ionic compounds in the molten state. • Be able to explain the formation Of the products in the electrolysis of molten lead bromide using inert electrodes.

E75938CC-AD08-43A1-8504-A87323161739.displayText: Be able to write half equations for reactions occurring at the anode and cathode in electrolysis
E75938CC-AD08-43A1-8504-A87323161739.level3: Be able to write half equations for reactions occurring at the anode and cathode in electrolysis

D5FE0604-0038-466F-BEA5-386B21925202.displayText: If you pass an electric current through an ionic substance that's molten or in solution
D5FE0604-0038-466F-BEA5-386B21925202.level3: If you pass an electric current through an ionic substance that's molten or in solution

E3034A64-916C-4AC5-8AA4-393BA9FD90E9.displayText: the ions in the liquid or solution will move towards the electrodes, where they can react, causing the ionic substance to decompose.
E3034A64-916C-4AC5-8AA4-393BA9FD90E9.level4: the ions in the liquid or solution will move towards the electrodes, where they can react, causing the ionic substance to decompose.

41CC375C-8675-4AC4-8FCF-35870F89E391.displayText: This process of breaking down a substance using electricity is called electrolysis.
41CC375C-8675-4AC4-8FCF-35870F89E391.level3: This process of breaking down a substance using electricity is called electrolysis.

9A205D0D-C6E1-41FA-95A8-2B51BFD5B6A2.displayText: Electrolysis requires a liquid to conduct the electricity, called the electrolyte.
9A205D0D-C6E1-41FA-95A8-2B51BFD5B6A2.level2: Electrolysis requires a liquid to conduct the electricity, called the electrolyte.

F06F22A4-5BAA-44E2-BDD0-6E0C5E3C96C0.displayText: Electrolytes contain free ions — they're usually a molten or dissolved ionic compound (see Figure 1).
F06F22A4-5BAA-44E2-BDD0-6E0C5E3C96C0.level2: Electrolytes contain free ions — they're usually a molten or dissolved ionic compound (see Figure 1).

AD7D8A38-6AA2-41AE-8ED6-88CD8AB93D26.displayText: In either case, it's the free ions which conduct the electricity and allow the whole thing to work.
AD7D8A38-6AA2-41AE-8ED6-88CD8AB93D26.level2: In either case, it's the free ions which conduct the electricity and allow the whole thing to work.

92DA3EBF-CC15-4997-B853-41E09E805248.displayText: Electrolysis is based on an electrical circuit that includes an electrolyte and two electrodes
92DA3EBF-CC15-4997-B853-41E09E805248.level2: Electrolysis is based on an electrical circuit that includes an electrolyte and two electrodes

B1D4DE95-0414-4AF3-A4C2-1860BDC6EB79.displayText: an electrode is a solid that conducts electricity and is submerged in the electrolyte In electrolysis,
B1D4DE95-0414-4AF3-A4C2-1860BDC6EB79.level3: an electrode is a solid that conducts electricity and is submerged in the electrolyte In electrolysis,

F727C365-6B2D-47C0-903C-D30443DC47D8.displayText: the electrodes are placed into the electrolyte and ions move from one electrode to the other — this allows the conduction of electricity through the circuit.
F727C365-6B2D-47C0-903C-D30443DC47D8.level3: the electrodes are placed into the electrolyte and ions move from one electrode to the other — this allows the conduction of electricity through the circuit.

A4276704-D73A-41A2-BE2C-E68033492E3B.displayText: The positive ions (cations) in the electrolyte will move towards the negative electrode (the cathode) and gain electrons.
A4276704-D73A-41A2-BE2C-E68033492E3B.level2: The positive ions (cations) in the electrolyte will move towards the negative electrode (the cathode) and gain electrons.

F9E19A20-0BEA-4C5A-84C2-9E112CD226C8.displayText: The negative ions (anions) in the electrolyte will move towards the positive electrode (the anode) and lose electrons.
F9E19A20-0BEA-4C5A-84C2-9E112CD226C8.level2: The negative ions (anions) in the electrolyte will move towards the positive electrode (the anode) and lose electrons.

3F989819-4CE2-4565-979D-95F64F8257F5.displayText: As ions gain or lose electrons they become atoms or molecules and are discharged (released) from the electrolyte. These atoms or molecules are the products of electrolysis.
3F989819-4CE2-4565-979D-95F64F8257F5.level2: As ions gain or lose electrons they become atoms or molecules and are discharged (released) from the electrolyte. These atoms or molecules are the products of electrolysis.

307E695C-68ED-4D0D-A378-975CF031D92D.displayText: Electrolysis always involves an oxidation reaction and a reduction reaction.
307E695C-68ED-4D0D-A378-975CF031D92D.level2: Electrolysis always involves an oxidation reaction and a reduction reaction.

1A3CD67C-88F9-42A0-B50D-B558BAACD054.displayText: Reduction is occurring at the negative electrode as the positive ions are gaining electrons.
1A3CD67C-88F9-42A0-B50D-B558BAACD054.level2: Reduction is occurring at the negative electrode as the positive ions are gaining electrons.

3FC2BFF9-48DE-416C-BC1C-2190F175EF7F.displayText: Oxidation occurs at the positive electrode as the negative ions are losing electrons.
3FC2BFF9-48DE-416C-BC1C-2190F175EF7F.level2: Oxidation occurs at the positive electrode as the negative ions are losing electrons.

411879EF-0EC2-4E41-8180-7C554C8EAE42.displayText: Binary compounds are ionic compounds containing two elements which are ions — a positive metal ion and a negative non-metal ion.
411879EF-0EC2-4E41-8180-7C554C8EAE42.level2: Binary compounds are ionic compounds containing two elements which are ions — a positive metal ion and a negative non-metal ion.

F86732E7-6D3C-49CE-BB30-C9E735325B26.displayText: Solid ionic compounds cannot be electrolysed because the ions are in fixed positions and can't move.
F86732E7-6D3C-49CE-BB30-C9E735325B26.level2: Solid ionic compounds cannot be electrolysed because the ions are in fixed positions and can't move.

CE31EF8F-2055-409E-9E7A-F45C01A2ABA8.displayText: However, molten ionic compounds can be electrolysed because the ions can move freely and conduct electricity.
CE31EF8F-2055-409E-9E7A-F45C01A2ABA8.level2: However, molten ionic compounds can be electrolysed because the ions can move freely and conduct electricity.

A81A13E3-F31E-4C2A-A6DD-D75494F35CF1.displayText: Electrolysis of molten binary compounds gives the neutral metal and non-metal elements.
A81A13E3-F31E-4C2A-A6DD-D75494F35CF1.level2: Electrolysis of molten binary compounds gives the neutral metal and non-metal elements.

D00BE6FE-11A6-4101-9D61-2BC6071ACBA7.displayText: During the electrolysis of these substances, the metal ions move to the cathode and gain electrons to become neutral, while the non-metal ions move to the anode and lose electrons to become neutral.
D00BE6FE-11A6-4101-9D61-2BC6071ACBA7.level2: During the electrolysis of these substances, the metal ions move to the cathode and gain electrons to become neutral, while the non-metal ions move to the anode and lose electrons to become neutral.
